# Wi-Fi and Remote Work Security

**Staying secure outside the office**

::: danger
**Public Wi-Fi Risks:**
- Unencrypted networks expose data
- Fake hotspots steal credentials
- Man-in-the-middle attacks
- Malware distribution
:::

**Best Practices for Remote Work:**
- Use company VPN always
- Avoid public Wi-Fi for sensitive work
- Keep software updated
- Lock screen when away
- Use privacy screens in public

@notes:
- Many employees work remotely regularly
- Public Wi-Fi particularly dangerous
- VPN mandatory for company access
- Physical security important too

---

# Physical Security Awareness

**Digital security extends to physical spaces**

**Office Security Measures:**
- Never hold doors for strangers (tailgating)
- Display visitor badges clearly
- Lock workstations when away
- Keep sensitive documents secure
- Report suspicious individuals

**Home Office Security:**
- Position screens away from windows
- Use privacy screens for video calls
- Secure documents and devices
- Install security updates promptely

@notes:
- Physical access often easier than digital
- Tailgating very common attack vector
- Home office security often overlooked
- Privacy screens protect from shoulder surfing

---

# Incident Response Procedure

**What to do if you suspect a security incident:**

<<mermaid>>
  flowchart TD
      A[Suspicious Activity Detected] --> B[Do NOT Click/Download]
      B --> C[Disconnect Network]
      C --> D[Report to IT Security]
      D --> E[Document What Happened]
      E --> F[Follow IT Instructions]
      
      style A fill:#ff9800,color:#fff
      style D fill:#2196f3,color:#fff
      style F fill:#4caf50,color:#fff

**Report First, Investigate Later**

::: info
**Security Team Contacts:**
- **Email:** security@{{company}}.com
- **Phone:** ext. 9911 (internal) | 555-SEC-HELP
- **Urgent:** Page security on-call team
:::

@notes:
- Speed crucial in incident response
- Don't click links if suspicious
- Network disconnect prevents spread
- IT security trained for incident handling

